  "text": "To demonstrate whether the beneficial effects of endogenous apoE3 could be harnessed as a therapeutic strategy, vehicle or COG1410 (1 mg/kg) was injected intravenously in C57-BL/6 mice at 30 minutes and 4 hours after ICH induction (nϭ8/ group). Although there was no difference in hemorrhage volume assessed at 7 days (24.3Ϯ1.17 in vehicle-treated vs 23.5Ϯ3.02 mm 3 in COG1410-treated), animals treated with doses of apoE-mimetic peptide demonstrated a durable improvement in functional outcomes, extended to 7 days to assess the possibility of a \"ceiling effect\" for COG1410 by Rotorod latencies (Figure 5A ; PϽ0.01) and neuroseverity scores (PϽ0.01) that persisted over the course of testing. Additionally, sham-operated animals did not demonstrate any functional deficits after injury. This was associated with a reduction in the brain water content in the injured hemisphere attributable to cerebral edema at 24 hours after injury (nϭ5/ group; 78.7Ϯ0.9 in vehicle-treated vs 75.5Ϯ0.5% in COG1410-treated; PϽ0.05). Finally, to evaluate the role of inflammation in the development of cerebral edema and its influence on functional outcomes, we performed quantitative real-time polymerase chain reaction in a separate cohort of animals (nϭ5/group) at 6 hours after ICH induction for the inflammatory cytokines eNOS, IL-6, and TNF-␣. Hemorrhage was again associated with an upregulation of all cytokines at 6 hours in the injured hemisphere of WT mice (TNF-␣: [CITATION_1] ever, when given the apoE-mimetic peptide, both IL-6 and eNOS were significantly reduced (IL-6: 22.77Ϯ3.24 in vehicle-treated vs 9.52Ϯ2.95 in COG1410-treated; eNOS: 1.52Ϯ0.05 in vehicle-treated vs 1.21Ϯ0.08 in COG1410-treated; PϽ0.01). These data suggest that the administration of an apoE-mimetic peptide influences neurological behavioral outcomes by downregulating inflammation resulting in less posthemorrhagic cerebral edema.",
